## Section II: Business & Systems Analysis

### Knowledge Area Overview

Business and systems analysis involves identifying organizational needs, modeling existing and proposed systems, and recommending technology solutions aligned with business objectives. This skill set requires both technical understanding of IT systems and business acumen to translate requirements into actionable solutions.

**How this maps to the Waystar Security Analyst role:** Security analysts must analyze system behavior, identify anomalies, and translate technical findings into clear recommendations—skills directly grounded in systems analysis methodology.

---

### Evidence Items

**CIS 495 — IT Strategic Assessment: The Hope Buss Nonprofit**
In this course, I completed a formal IT Strategic Assessment for The Hope Buss, a Louisville-area nonprofit. My work covered Sections 3 and 4 of the assessment, which documented the organization's current business processes and existing IT environment. I mapped workflows, identified technology gaps, and assessed how current systems aligned with organizational goals. This project required structured analysis, stakeholder awareness, and formal written communication of findings—all core competencies in business and systems analysis.

**CIS 420 — Capstone: Website Redesign Project (Team Matrix / Data Pirates)**
As part of a team, I participated in the analysis and redesign of The Hope Buss's public-facing website using the Wix platform. The project followed a structured development lifecycle including requirements gathering, design iteration, peer review, and stakeholder demos. I contributed to documentation including meeting minutes, peer feedback evaluations for competing teams, and project milestone tracking. This experience mirrors how security teams document findings, coordinate across stakeholders, and deliver iterative improvements.

**IT Leadership Coursework — IVK Case Studies & Vendor Selection**
In this coursework, I analyzed fictional IT leadership scenarios (IVK company case studies) covering vendor selection, SLA development, and innovation evaluation frameworks including the 2×2 risk matrix and Xerox PARC innovation model. These exercises built my ability to evaluate technology options against business constraints—a skill directly applicable to security tool selection and risk prioritization.

